DataElementConcept.preferredName: Disease Malignant Neoplasm Excision Or Biopsy
DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Any abnormal condition of the body or mind that causes discomfort, dysfunction, or distress to the person affected or those in contact with the person. The term is often used broadly to include injuries, disabilities, syndromes, symptoms, deviant behaviors, and atypical variations of structure and function.:A tumor composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas, Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas._The surgical removal of a lesion, often as part of a biopsy and with healthy margins._An article used to connect words, phrases, or clauses representing alternatives; used to connect alternative terms for the same thing; used in correlation; used to correct or rephrase what was previously said; otherwise._The removal of tissue specimens or fluid from the living body for microscopic examination, performed to establish a diagnosis.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A definite pathologic process with a characteristic set of signs and symptoms. It may affect the whole body or any of its parts, and its etiology, pathology, and prognosis may be known or unknown.

Concepts.definition: Any abnormal condition of the body or mind that causes discomfort, dysfunction, or distress to the person affected or those in contact with the person. The term is often used broadly to include injuries, disabilities, syndromes, symptoms, deviant behaviors, and atypical variations of structure and function.

Property.preferredDefinition: A tumor composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas (adenocarcinomas or squamous cell carcinomas), Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas.:The act of cutting out; the surgical removal of part or all of a structure or organ.:An article used to connect words, phrases, or clauses representing alternatives; used to connect alternative terms for the same thing; used in correlation; used to correct or rephrase what was previously said; otherwise.:The removal of tissue specimens or fluid from the living body for microscopic examination, performed to establish a diagnosis.

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas, Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas.
The surgical removal of a lesion, often as part of a biopsy and with healthy margins.

An article used to connect words, phrases, or clauses representing alternatives; used to connect alternative terms for the same thing; used in correlation; used to correct or rephrase what was previously said; otherwise.
The removal of tissue specimens or fluid from the living body for microscopic examination, performed to establish a diagnosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: That part of the central nervous system contained within the cranium, comprising the prosencephalon, mesencephalon, and rhombencephalon. Functions include muscle control and coordination, sensory reception and integration, speech production, memory storage, and the elaboration of thought and emotions.

Concepts.definition: An organ composed of grey and white matter containing billions of neurons that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. It is protected by the bony cranium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower pair of vocal folds located below the glottis, which are the primary source of phonation

Concepts.definition: The upper, rounded portion of the uterus which is opposite from the cervix.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the autonomic nervous system comprising paired, paraspinal sympathetic trunks together with their branches, plexi, and subsidiary ganglia; it functions to mobilize the body for activity and opposes the physiological effects of the parasympathetic nervous system.

Concepts.definition: The part of the autonomic nervous system comprising paired, paraspinal sympathetic trunks together with their branches, plexi, and subsidiary ganglia; it functions to mobilize the body for activity and opposes the physiological effects of the parasympathetic nervous system.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The Corpus uteri, or body of uterus, is the part of the uterus above the isthmus, comprising about two thirds of the non-pregnant organ.

Concepts.definition: A small, tubular passageway that transports saliva from the submandibular gland into the floor of the mouth, exiting adjacent to the lingual frenulum.

Concepts.definition: The bony, basin-shaped structure formed by the hipbones and the base of the backbone supporting the lower limbs in humans.

Concepts.definition: A hollow tube that starts posterior to the mouth and nasal cavity and ends superior to the trachea and esophagus.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the abdominal cavity, intestine, mesentery, and pelvic organs. It consists of the parietal peritoneum and the visceral peritoneum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ that is part of the lymphatic system, in which T lymphocytes grow and multiply. The thymus is in the chest behind the breastbone.

Concepts.definition: A bi-lobed organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is located in the upper anterior portion of the chest, behind the sternum. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and fewer epithelial cells. Connective tissue septa separate the lobes into lobules. The lobules contain an outer portion (cortical zone) which is rich in lymphocytes and an inner portion (medullary zone) which is rich in epithelial cells. It is an organ essential for the development of the immune system. Its function is the maturation of the progenitor lymphoid cells to thymocytes and subsequently to mature T-cells. It reaches its greatest weight at puberty and subsequently begins to involute.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the cervix which is lined by single columnar epithelium (mucosa).

SYN ren, nephros.

The kidneys filter and secrete metabolic products and minerals from the blood, thus maintaining homeostasis. On the superior pole of each kidney there is an adrenal gland. ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower right and left chambers of the heart. The right pumps venous blood into the lungs and the left pumps oxygenated blood into the systemic arterial circulation. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: One of the two lower chambers of the heart that receives blood from an atrium and pumps blood to the arteries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of two large, bilateral muscles overlying the upper, anterior chest wall, which has two heads: the clavicular head, which originates on the medial half of the clavicle, and the sternal head, which originates on the sternum and the first six costal cartilages; the muscles insert onto the lateral lip of the intertubercular groove of the humerus and the crest of the greater tubercle of the humerus respectively, and function to flex, adduct, and medially rotate the shoulder joint.

Concepts.definition: Either of two large, bilateral muscles overlying the upper, anterior chest wall, which has two heads: the clavicular head, which originates on the medial half of the clavicle, and the sternal head, which originates on the sternum and the first six costal cartilages; the muscles insert onto the lateral lip of the intertubercular groove of the humerus and the crest of the greater tubercle of the humerus respectively, and function to flex, adduct, and medially rotate the shoulder joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ behind the lower part of the stomach that is the shape of a fish and about the size of a hand.  It is a compound gland composed of both exocrine and endocrine tissues.  The endocrine pancreas makes insulin so that the body can use glucose (sugar) for energy. The exocrine pancreas makes enzymes that help the body digest food.  Spread all over the pancreas are areas called the Islets of Langerhans. The cells in these areas each have a special purpose. The alpha cells make glucagon, which raises the level of glucose in the blood; the beta cells make insulin; the delta cells make somatostatin. There are also PP cells and D1 cells, about which little is known.

Concepts.definition: An organ behind the lower part of the stomach that is the shape of a fish and about the size of a hand. It is a compound gland composed of both exocrine and endocrine tissues. The endocrine pancreas makes insulin so that the body can use glucose (sugar) for energy. The exocrine pancreas makes enzymes that help the body digest food. Spread all over the pancreas are areas called the Islets of Langerhans. The cells in these areas each have a special purpose. The alpha cells make glucagon, which raises the level of glucose in the blood; the beta cells make insulin; the delta cells make somatostatin. There are also PP cells and D1 cells, about which little is known.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the human body between the neck and the diaphragm or the corresponding part in other vertebrates.

Concepts.definition: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen. The shape of the chest is often regarded as potential insight into a disease process, as in the case of barrel chest and respiratory dysfunction.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any component associated with the pancreas that is different from the one(s) previously specified or mentioned.

Concepts.definition: Any component associated with the pancreas that is different from the one(s) previously specified or mentioned.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow.

Concepts.definition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The area located between the anus and vulva in females, and anus and scrotum in males.

Concepts.definition: The area located between the anus and vulva in females, and anus and scrotum in males.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance. The outer ear consists of the auricle, the ear canal as well as the tympanic membrane. The middle ear is made up of an air-filled cavity behind the tympanic membrane that contains the ossicles (malleus, incus and stapes). The inner ear is made up of the cochlea needed for hearing and the vestibular apparatus required for balance.

Concepts.definition: A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance. The outer ear consists of the auricle, the ear canal as well as the tympanic membrane. The middle ear is made up of an air-filled cavity behind the tympanic membrane that contains the ossicles (malleus, incus and stapes). The inner ear is made up of the cochlea needed for hearing and the vestibular apparatus required for balance.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the ear including the eardrum and ossicles. The middle ear leads to the inner ear.

Concepts.definition: The part of the ear including the eardrum and ossicles. The middle ear leads to the inner ear.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The middle one of the three pairs of embryonic renal organs developed in most vertebrates; its duct system is retained in the male as the epididymis and ductus deferens.

Concepts.definition: The middle one of the three pairs of embryonic renal organs developed in most vertebrates; its duct system is retained in the male as the epididymis and ductus deferens.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The twelfth cranial nerve. It arises from the hypoglossal nucleus and leads to the tongue.

Concepts.definition: The twelfth cranial nerve. It arises from the hypoglossal nucleus and leads to the tongue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fold of lymphatic tissue covered by ciliated epithelium at the very back of the nose, in the roof of the nasopharynx.

Concepts.definition: A fold of lymphatic tissue covered by ciliated epithelium at the very back of the nose, in the roof of the nasopharynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer part of the adrenal gland (a small organ on top of each kidney). The adrenal cortex makes androgen and corticosteroid hormones.

Concepts.definition: The outer region of the adrenal gland consisting of the zona glomerulosa, the zona fasciculata, and the zona reticularis. The adrenal cortex produces and secretes mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids, and adrenal androgens.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pyramidal-shaped, thin-walled, air-filled cavity located in the maxilla. It is lined by mucus membrane and periosteum (mucoperiosteum) which contains cilia. It is adjacent to the nasal cavity and communicates with the middle meatus of the nose. It is the largest paranasal sinus and is composed of three recesses: alveolar, zygomatic, and infraorbital.

Concepts.definition: A pyramidal-shaped, thin-walled, air-filled cavity located in the maxilla. It is lined by mucus membrane and periosteum (mucoperiosteum) which contains cilia. It is adjacent to the nasal cavity and communicates with the middle meatus of the nose. It is the largest paranasal sinus and is composed of three recesses: alveolar, zygomatic, and infraorbital.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A duct in the embryo draining the mesonephric tubules.

Concepts.definition: A duct in the embryo draining the mesonephric tubules.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to the lower trunk and the legs.

Concepts.definition: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to the lower trunk and the legs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The delicate, highly vascular, innermost membrane encasing the brain and spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The delicate, highly vascular, innermost membrane encasing the brain and spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The inner part of the adrenal gland; it synthesizes, stores and releases catecholamines. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: The inner region of the adrenal gland. The adrenal medulla produces, stores, and secretes epinephrine and norepinephrine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sinus of the meatuses of the nasal cavity.

Concepts.definition: A sinus of the meatuses of the nasal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper jawbone in vertebrates: it is fused to the cranium.

Concepts.definition: The upper jawbone in vertebrates; it is fused to the cranium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A depression of the skull base lying posterior and inferior to the anterior cranial fossa and separated from the posterior cranial fossa by the clivus and the petrous crest. It supports the temporal lobes of the cerebrum and the pituitary gland.

Concepts.definition: A depression of the skull base lying posterior and inferior to the anterior cranial fossa and separated from the posterior cranial fossa by the clivus and the petrous crest. It supports the temporal lobes of the cerebrum and the pituitary gland.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The superior portion of the body of the stomach above the level of the cardiac notch.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the stomach that lies above the cardiac notch. It allows for the accumulation of gases produced by chemical digestion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded.

Concepts.definition: The terminal section of the alimentary canal, which extends from the anorectal junction and ends at the anal opening.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Bile ducts are passageways that carry bile. Two major bile ducts come together into a "trunk"-the common bile duct which empties into the upper part of the small intestine (the part next to the stomach).

Concepts.definition: Bile ducts are passageways that carry bile. Two major bile ducts come together into a "trunk"-the common bile duct which empties into the upper part of the small intestine (the part next to the stomach).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small salivary gland located in the oral cavity.  It produces saliva.

Concepts.definition: A small salivary gland located within the aerodigestive tract.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line.

Concepts.definition: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The main section of the digestive tube that connects the esophagus to the small intestine. The body proper excludes the upper and lower sections of the fundus and pyloric portion respectively.

Concepts.definition: The main section of the digestive tube that connects the esophagus to the small intestine. The body proper excludes the upper and lower sections of the fundus and pyloric portion respectively.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the ducts conveying bile between the liver and the intestine, including hepatic, cystic, and common bile duct.

Concepts.definition: Any of the ducts conveying bile between the liver and the intestine, including hepatic, cystic, and common bile duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the 12 paired nerves that originate in the brain stem.

Concepts.definition: Any of the 12 paired nerves that originate in the brain stem.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rounded prominence of adipose tissue overlying the pubic symphysis and adjacent pubic bone.

Concepts.definition: A rounded prominence of adipose tissue overlying the pubic symphysis and adjacent pubic bone.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscle of mastication originating from the zygomatic arch.

Concepts.definition: A muscle of mastication originating from the zygomatic arch.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (DYE-a-fram) The thin muscle below the lungs and heart that separates the chest from the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: Fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity. It increases the volume of the thoracic cavity through contractions, thus facilitating respiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The initial part of the pyloric canal of the stomach.  This site contains endocrine cells that produce gastrin and somatostatin.

Concepts.definition: The initial part of the pyloric canal of the stomach. This site contains endocrine cells that produce gastrin and somatostatin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pear-shaped organ just below the liver that stores the bile secreted by the liver, delivering the bile through the bile ducts into the intestines to help with digestion.

Concepts.definition: A pear-shaped organ located under the liver that stores and concentrates bile secreted by the liver. From the gallbladder the bile is delivered through the bile ducts into the intestine thereby aiding the digestion of fat-containing foods.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A triangular muscle in the back, connected to the vertebral column, arm, and shoulder. Its action involves adduction, medial rotation, and extension of the arm.

Concepts.definition: A triangular muscle in the back, connected to the vertebral column, arm, and shoulder. Its action involves adduction, medial rotation, and extension of the arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin membrane that lines the fluid-filled spaces in the brain and spinal cord. It is made up of a type of glial cell called an ependymal cell.

Concepts.definition: A thin membrane that lines the ventricles of the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.

Concepts.definition: Ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower part of the stomach that connects to the duodenum.

Concepts.definition: The lower part of the stomach that connects to the duodenum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus.

Concepts.definition: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated concept definition to match current NCIt. 4.5.18 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two small oblong bones placed side by side at the middle and upper part of the face.

Concepts.definition: One of two small oblong bones placed side by side at the middle and upper part of the face.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: White matter pathway, flanked by nuclear masses, consisting of both afferent and efferent fibers projecting between the cerebral cortex and the brainstem. It consists of three distinct parts: the anterior limb, posterior limb, and genu. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: A white matter structure in the subcortical region of the brain that contains a high concentration of motor and sensory projection nerve fibers. It consists of the anterior limb, genu, posterior limb, and the retrolentiform and sublentiform parts.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small cartilagenous flap-like valve that closes over the larynx during swallowing to prevent food entering the lungs.

Concepts.definition: A small cartilagenous flap-like valve that closes over the larynx during swallowing to prevent food entering the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: not classifiable to C16.1 to C16.4

Concepts.definition: The right border of the stomach.  It is concave in shape and extends from the cardiac orifice to the pyloric orifice.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small, fingerlike pouch that sticks out from the cecum (the first part of the large intestine near the end of the small intestine).

Concepts.definition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The thin wall between the two nasal cavities.

Concepts.definition: The thin wall between the two nasal cavities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sheet or band of fibrous connective tissue enveloping, separating, or binding together muscles, organs, and other soft structures of the body.

Concepts.definition: A sheet or band of fibrous connective tissue enveloping, separating, or binding together muscles, organs, and other soft structures of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A light and spongy bone that is cubical in shape. This bone is positioned at the anterior part of the cranium, sitting between the two orbits, at the roof of the nose. It consists of four parts: a horizontal or cribriform plate; a perpendicular plate; and two lateral masses or labyrinths.

Concepts.definition: A light and spongy bone that is cubical in shape. This bone is positioned at the anterior part of the cranium, sitting between the two orbits, at the roof of the nose. It consists of four parts: a horizontal or cribriform plate; a perpendicular plate; and two lateral masses or labyrinths.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lateral and inferior border of the stomach.  Attached to it is the greater omentum.

Concepts.definition: The lateral and inferior border of the stomach. Attached to it is the greater omentum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tube-like structure that conveys tears from the lacrimal sac to the nasal cavity.

Concepts.definition: A tube-like structure that conveys tears from the lacrimal sac to the nasal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

Concepts.definition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer membranous connective tissue layer of the heart tissue.

Concepts.definition: The outer membranous connective tissue layer of the heart tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin membrane of skin with the purpose of covering and protecting an eye.

Concepts.definition: A thin membrane of skin with the purpose of covering and protecting an eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum.

Concepts.definition: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the two channels of the nose, from the point where they divide to the external opening.

Concepts.definition: One of the two channels of the nose, from the point where they divide to the external opening.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.

Concepts.definition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Lymph node located adjacent to the diaphragm.

Concepts.definition: Lymph node located adjacent to the diaphragm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The 7th cranial nerve. The facial nerve has two parts, the larger motor root which may be called the facial nerve proper, and the smaller intermediate or sensory root. Together they provide efferent innervation to the muscles of facial expression and to the lacrimal and salivary glands, and convey afferent information for taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue and for touch from the external ear. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: Cranial nerve VII, which originates in the brainstem between the pons and the medulla. It controls the facial expression muscles and transports taste and sensation from the tongue and mouth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A congenital pouch in the distal ileum. It may cause painless rectal bleeding and bowel obstruction.

Concepts.definition: A congenital pouch in the distal ileum. It may cause painless rectal bleeding and bowel obstruction.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A group of six muscles that are responsible for moving the eye.

Concepts.definition: A group of extrinsic muscles that are responsible for moving the eye and lifting the eyelid. These include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, inferior oblique, and levator palpebrae superioris, all innervated by CN III (oculomotor nerve), superior oblique, innervated by CN IV (trochlear nerve), lateral rectus, innervated by CN VI (abducens nerve).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ present in some vertebrates during embryonic gestation that surrounds the fetus and provides it with nutrients and oxygen, facilitates gas and waste exchange between the fetus and mother, and provides parasitic cloaking from the mother's immune system by excretion of neurokinin B.

Concepts.definition: An organ present in some vertebrates during embryonic gestation that surrounds the fetus and provides it with nutrients and oxygen, facilitates gas and waste exchange between the fetus and mother, and provides parasitic cloaking from the mother's immune system by excretion of neurokinin B.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the colon that connects to the descending colon above and the rectum below.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the colon that connects to the descending colon above and the rectum below.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An artery that starts within the inguinal region and extends to the lower extremities.

Concepts.definition: An artery that starts within the inguinal region and extends to the lower extremities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The first part of the colon (large intestine) that starts in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen and ends at the transverse colon in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: The first part of the colon (large intestine) that starts in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen and ends at the transverse colon in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The joint between the head of the lower mandible and the temporal bone.

Concepts.definition: The joint between the head of the lower mandible and the temporal bone.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue lining the chambers of the heart.

Concepts.definition: The layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue lining the chambers of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bile ducts that pass through and drain bile from the liver.

Concepts.definition: The bile ducts which are located within the liver. They include the small interlobular bile ducts, intrahepatic large bile ducts, and the intrahepatic portions of the left and right hepatic ducts.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Lymph nodes found within the head and neck region of the body, which drain into the deep cervical nodes, either directly or indirectly. These include the occipital, mastoid, parotid, facial, retropharyngeal, submandibular, submental, lingual and cervical lymph nodes. Any lymph node located in the head or neck.

Concepts.definition: Lymph nodes found within the head and neck region of the body, which drain into the deep cervical nodes, either directly or indirectly. These include the occipital, mastoid, parotid, facial, retropharyngeal, submandibular, submental, lingual and cervical lymph nodes. Any lymph node located in the head or neck.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The aspect of the nasopharyngeal wall that is located on the side.  It contains the pharyngeal opening of the auditory tube.

Concepts.definition: The aspect of the nasopharyngeal wall that is located on the side.  It contains the pharyngeal opening of the auditory tube.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia. The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Other structures of the knee joint include the upper part of the fibula, located below and parallel to the tibia, and the patella which moves as the knee bends.

Concepts.definition: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia. The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Other structures of the knee joint include the upper part of the fibula, located below and parallel to the tibia, and the patella which moves as the knee bends.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The duct system that transports bile from its origination by hepatocytes in the liver to the small intestine. It is comprised of the common bile duct that connects the liver and gall bladder to the small intestine and the cystic duct that connects the gall bladder to the common bile duct.

Concepts.definition: The system that transports bile from the hepatocytes in the liver to the small intestine. It is comprised of the intrahepatic bile ducts, hepatic ducts, common bile duct, cystic duct, and the gallbladder.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fibroserous sac surrounding the heart and the roots of the great vessels.

Concepts.definition: A conical membranous sac filled with serous fluid in which the heart as well as the roots of the aorta and other large blood vessels are contained.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any lymph node within the thoracic cavity.

Concepts.definition: Any lymph node within the thoracic cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An oval shaped cavity at the upper extremity of the nasal duct.

Concepts.definition: An oval shaped cavity at the upper extremity of the nasal duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The anterior aspect of the nasopharynx.

Concepts.definition: The anterior aspect of the nasopharynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.

Concepts.definition: A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated concept to reflect EVS definition_02.19.19

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The junction of the common bile and main pancreatic ducts, which protrudes into the medial aspect of the descending duodenum at the major duodenal papilla. The flow of bile and pancreatic juices into the duodenum through the Ampulla of Vater is controlled by the sphincter of Oddi.

Concepts.definition: The junction of the common bile and main pancreatic ducts, which protrudes into the medial aspect of the descending duodenum at the major duodenal papilla. The flow of bile and pancreatic juices into the duodenum through the Ampulla of Vater is controlled by the sphincter of Oddi.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated concept definition to use current NCIt. 6.4.18 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any lymph node within the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: Any lymph node within the abdomen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lymphoid follicles on the dorsal surface in the posterior region of the tongue.

Concepts.definition: The lymphoid follicles on the dorsal surface in the posterior region of the tongue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus.

Concepts.definition: The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A nerve network originating from C5 to T1 that supplies cutaneous and muscular innervation to the arm and hand.

Concepts.definition: A nerve network originating from C5 to T1 that supplies cutaneous and muscular innervation to the arm and hand.

PermissibleValues.value: Lymph Node of Inguinal Region or Leg

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Lymph Node of Inguinal Region or Leg
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any lymph node that is located in the inguinal region or in either leg.

Concepts.longName: Lymph Node of Inguinal Region or Leg
Concepts.definition: Any lymph node that is located in the inguinal region or in either leg.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The connection point between two bones or skeletal elements. The joint may be fixed or movable.

Concepts.definition: The connection point between two bones or skeletal elements. The joint may be fixed or movable.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The soft fleshy portion of the lower external ear composed of areolar and adipose connective tissues.

Concepts.definition: The soft fleshy portion of the lower external ear composed of areolar and adipose connective tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the hypopharynx demarcated by a plane drawn at the level of the tip of the epiglottis to a plane at the inferior border of the cricoid.

Concepts.definition: The region of the hypopharynx demarcated by a plane drawn at the level of the tip of the epiglottis to a plane at the inferior border of the cricoid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).

Concepts.definition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A band of fibrous connective tissue that joins bone to muscle.

Concepts.definition: A band of fibrous connective tissue that joins bone to muscle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any lymph node within the abdominal pelvic region.

Concepts.definition: Any lymph node within the abdominal pelvic region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the five spinal nerves originating from the lumbar region.

Concepts.definition: Any of the five spinal nerves originating from the lumbar region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of skeletal muscle. It corresponds to the superior part of the upper third topographic segment of the esophagus.

Concepts.definition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of skeletal muscle. It corresponds to the superior part of the upper third topographic segment of the esophagus.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: 5.12.21 Added definition where none was previously available. mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Band of fibrous tissue connecting bone to bone or cartilage to bone thereby supporting or strengthening a joint.

Concepts.definition: Band of fibrous tissue connecting bone to bone or cartilage to bone thereby supporting or strengthening a joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (BRON-kee-olz) The tiny branches of air tubes in the lungs.

Concepts.definition: The smallest subdivisions of the bronchial tree, which are both acartilagenous and aglandular.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body.

Concepts.definition: The structural organ comprised of specialized connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated concept definition with current NCIt. 4.5.18 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It includes the middle third topographic segment, as well as parts of the upper and lower thirds.

Concepts.definition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It includes the middle third topographic segment, as well as parts of the upper and lower thirds.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fold of skin covering the tip of the penis.

Concepts.definition: A fold of skin covering the tip of the penis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: In humans, the glands of the breast, consisting of fibrous tissue connecting the lobes and fatty tissue in between the lobes.

Concepts.definition: In humans, the glands of the breast, consisting of fibrous tissue connecting the lobes and fatty tissue in between the lobes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Striated muscles that are under voluntary control of the organism. They are connected at either or both ends to a bone and are utilized for locomotion and other movements. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: Striated muscles that are under voluntary control of the organism.  They are connected at either or both ends to a bone and are utilized for locomotion and other movements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the two principal arteries on both sides of the neck that supply blood to the head and neck; each divides into two branches, the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.

Concepts.definition: One of two arteries that supply oxygenated blood to the head and neck; the left common carotid branches from the aorta and the right common carotid from the innominate (brachiocephalic artery).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It corresponds to the inferior part of the lower third topographic segment of the esophagus.

Concepts.definition: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It corresponds to the inferior part of the lower third topographic segment of the esophagus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A lymph node located in the mediastinum. Mediastinal lymph nodes are arranged in three groups, one on the lateral, another on the medial, and a third on the anterior aspect of the vessels; the third group is, however, sometimes absent.

Concepts.definition: A lymph node located in the mediastinum. Mediastinal lymph nodes are arranged in three groups, one on the lateral, another on the medial, and a third on the anterior aspect of the vessels; the third group is, however, sometimes absent.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the contractile organs of the body.

Concepts.definition: One of the contractile organs of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The pigmented circle or ring of skin that surrounds the nipple.

Concepts.definition: The pigmented circle or ring of skin that surrounds the nipple.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The eight bones of the wrist: capitate bone, hamate bone, lunate bone (SEMILUNAR BONE), pisiform bone, SCAPHOID BONE, trapezium bone, trapezoid bone and triquetral bone.

Concepts.definition: Any of the small bones of the wrist joint, located between the radius and the ulna and the metacarpus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sebaceous gland in the eyelid that produces a specific type of sebum.

Concepts.definition: A sebaceous gland in the eyelid that produces a specific type of sebum.

Concepts.definition: A dome-shaped, transparent, avascular tissue covering the front of the eye. Concepts.definition: A sub-cortical, paired nuclei that, though migrated to the telencephalon, is a critical part of the basal ganglia, along with the caudate nucleus and the putamen, the latter of which it joins to form the lentiform nucleus. Each nucleus is subdivided into internal and external parts, called globus pallidus interna and globus pallidus externa, which are separated by an internal medullary lamina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An important supervisory center in the brain, rich in ganglia, nerve fibers, and synaptic connections. It is composed of several sections called nuclei, each of which controls a specific function. The hypothalamus regulates body temperature, blood pressure, heartbeat, metabolism of fats and carbohydrates, and sugar levels in the blood. Through direct attachment to the pituitary gland, the hypothalamus also meters secretions controlling water balance and milk production in the female. The role of the hypothalamus in awareness of pleasure and pain is well established in the laboratory. It is involved in the expression of emotions, such as fear and rage, and in sexual behaviors. Despite its numerous vital functions, the hypothalamus in humans accounts for only 1/300 of total brain weight, and is about the size of an almond. Structurally, it is joined to the thalamus; the two work together to monitor the sleep-wake cycle.

Concepts.definition: An important supervisory center in the brain, rich in ganglia, nerve fibers, and synaptic connections. It is composed of several sections called nuclei, each of which controls a specific function. The hypothalamus regulates body temperature, blood pressure, heartbeat, metabolism of fats and carbohydrates, and sugar levels in the blood. Through direct attachment to the pituitary gland, the hypothalamus also meters secretions controlling water balance and milk production in the female. The role of the hypothalamus in awareness of pleasure and pain is well established in the laboratory. It is involved in the expression of emotions, such as fear and rage, and in sexual behaviors. Despite its numerous vital functions, the hypothalamus in humans accounts for only 1/300 of total brain weight, and is about the size of an almond. Structurally, it is joined to the thalamus; the two work together to monitor the sleep-wake cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (THAL-a-muss) An area of the brain that helps process information from the senses and transmit it to other parts of the brain.

Concepts.definition: An ovoid mass composed predominantly of gray substance and associated laminae of white substance. The thalamus is divided into anterior, medial, and lateral parts. The function of the thalamus is to relay sensory impulses and cerebellar and basal ganglia projections to the cerebral cortex. The thalamus is positioned within the posterior part of the diencephalon forming most of each lateral wall of the third ventricle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge.

Concepts.definition: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the bundles of nerve fibers running to various organs and tissues of the body using chemical and electrical signals to transmit sensory and motor information from one body part to another.

Concepts.definition: Part of the peripheral nervous system composed of bundles of nerve fibers running to various organs and tissues of the body using chemical and electrical signals to transmit sensory and motor information from one body part to another.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. As a rule, the right lung is slightly larger than the left and is divided into three lobes (an upper, a middle, and a lower or basal), while the left has two lobes (an upper and a lower or basal). Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border.

Concepts.definition: One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. As a rule, the right lung is slightly larger than the left and is divided into three lobes (an upper, a middle, and a lower or basal), while the left has two lobes (an upper and a lower or basal). Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ that constitutes the external surface of the body.  It consists of the epidermis, dermis, and skin appendages.

Concepts.definition: An organ that constitutes the external surface of the body. It consists of the epidermis, dermis, and skin appendages.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Connective tissue composed of fat cells lodged in the meshes of areolar tissue.

Concepts.definition: A specialized form of connective tissue consisting primarily of adipocytes (fat cells), surrounded by a meshwork of collagen fibers.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bony prominence situated on the upper surface of the body of the sphenoid bone housing the pituitary gland.

Concepts.definition: A bony prominence situated on the upper surface of the body of the sphenoid bone housing the pituitary gland.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A part of the ear canal that is external to the ear drum.

Concepts.definition: A part of the ear canal that is external to the ear drum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the ear located within the temporal bone that is involved in both hearing and balance and includes the semicircular canals, vestibule, and cochlea. (from American Heritage Dictionary online)

Concepts.definition: The portion of the ear located within the temporal bone that is involved in both hearing and balance and includes the semicircular canals, vestibule, and cochlea. (from American Heritage Dictionary online)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tubular structure that runs from the middle ear to the nasopharynx and is approximately 3-4 cm length. Its lumen is roughly triangular and has average diameter of 2-3 mm. The lumen is lined by ciliated pseudostratified, columnar epithelium, which sweeps material from the middle ear to the nasopharynx. It is functionally collapsed at rest, with slight negative pressure present in the middle ear, and opens during swallowing, sneezing, and yawning.  It serves to ventilate pressure differences between the middle ear and nasopharynx. This tube also allows middle ear secretions to drain into the nasopharynx.

Concepts.definition: A tubular structure that runs from the middle ear to the nasopharynx and is approximately 3-4 cm length. Its lumen is roughly triangular and has average diameter of 2-3 mm. The lumen is lined by ciliated pseudostratified, columnar epithelium, which sweeps material from the middle ear to the nasopharynx. It is functionally collapsed at rest, with slight negative pressure present in the middle ear, and opens during swallowing, sneezing, and yawning.  It serves to ventilate pressure differences between the middle ear and nasopharynx. This tube also allows middle ear secretions to drain into the nasopharynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mucosal membranes located on the inside of the cheek, in the buccal cavity.

Concepts.definition: The mucosal membranes located on the inside of the cheek, in the buccal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A region in the brain that is located below the tentorium cerebelli and contains the cerebellum.

Concepts.definition: A region in the brain that is located below the tentorium cerebelli and contains the cerebellum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The uppermost portion of the brainstem located between the pons and the diencephalon.  The midbrain contains the cerebral peduncles, oculomotor, trochlear and red nuclei, substantia nigra and various other nuclei and tracts.

Concepts.definition: The uppermost portion of the brainstem located between the pons and the diencephalon. The midbrain contains the cerebral peduncles, oculomotor, trochlear and red nuclei, substantia nigra and various other nuclei and tracts.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Part of the central nervous system, located at the base of the brain, between the medulla oblongata and the midbrain. It is part of the brainstem.

Concepts.definition: The middle portion of the brainstem located between the midbrain and the medulla oblongata. The fourth ventricle lies dorsal to the pons which also contains the motor trigeminal nuclei and the abducens nuclei. The cerebellum contributes a large number of afferent fibers to the pons.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the brain that is located superior to the tentorium cerebelli.

Concepts.definition: The part of the brain that is located superior to the tentorium cerebelli.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The pancreatic tissue that contains the islets of Langerhans. It is responsible for the production and secretions of the pancreatic hormones.

Concepts.definition: A specialized region of tissue located within the parenchyma of the pancreas that contains a mixed population of distinct endocrine cells, including beta, alpha, pancreatic polypeptide, delta, and epsilon cells, which respectively produce and secrete insulin, glucagon, pancreatic polypeptide, somatostatin, and ghrelin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large irregular bone situated at the base and side of the skull, connected with the mandible via the temporomandibular joint. The temporal bone consists of the squamous, tympanic and petrous parts. The petrous portion of the temporal bone contains the vestibulocochlear organ of the inner ear. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: A large irregular bone situated at the base and side of the skull, connected with the mandible via the temporomandibular joint. The temporal bone consists of the squamous, tympanic and petrous parts. The petrous portion of the temporal bone contains the vestibulocochlear organ of the inner ear.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The division of the body lying between the neck and the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: The division of the body lying between the neck and the abdomen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The second longest bone of the skeleton. It is located on the medial side of the lower leg, articulating with the FIBULA laterally, the TALUS distally, and the FEMUR proximally.

Concepts.definition: A bone located between the femur and the tarsus, being part of the lower leg.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fifth set of paired nerves of the face that emerge from the brain steam. These nerves have sensory and motor functions in the face, oral cavity, and nasal cavity.

Concepts.definition: The fifth set of paired nerves of the face that emerge from the brain steam. These nerves have sensory and motor functions in the face, oral cavity, and nasal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cranial nerve that controls the superior oblique muscle of the eye.

Concepts.definition: The cranial nerve that controls the superior oblique muscle of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the bones that comprise the forearm. The largest aspect articulates with the humerus at the elbow joint and the smallest portion of the ulna articulates with the carpal bones in the wrist.

Concepts.definition: One of the bones that comprise the forearm. The largest aspect articulates with the humerus at the elbow joint and the smallest portion of the ulna articulates with the carpal bones in the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The pigmented layer of the eyeball between the tough, white outer coat of the eye and the retina.

Concepts.definition: The pigmented layer of the eyeball between the tough, white outer coat of the eye and the retina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tenth cranial nerve. It is the longest cranial nerve. It originates in the medulla and exits the cranium through the jugular foramen. It supplies various muscles, including muscles of the pharynx and soft palate.

Concepts.definition: The tenth cranial nerve. It is the longest cranial nerve. It originates in the medulla and exits the cranium through the jugular foramen. It supplies various muscles, including muscles of the pharynx and soft palate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Duct carrying spermatozoa.

Concepts.definition: Duct carrying spermatozoa.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A blood vessel that carries blood toward the heart.

Concepts.definition: A blood vessel that carries blood toward the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large vein that empties into the heart. It carries blood from the legs and feet and from organs in the abdomen and pelvis.

Concepts.definition: A large vein that returns blood from the lower half of the body to the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The large vein that carries blood from the head, neck, arms, and chest to the heart.

Concepts.definition: The large vein that terminates in the right atrium and transports deoxygenated blood from the head, neck, arms, and chest to the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large vein which returns blood from the head, neck and extremities to the heart.

Concepts.definition: A large vein which returns blood from the head, neck and extremities to the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pair of small bands of muscle that stretch from the thyroid cartilage in front to the arytenoid cartilage in back of the larynx. The vocal cords help prevent food entering the lungs and produce sound through vibration.

Concepts.definition: A pair of small bands of muscle that stretch from the thyroid cartilage in front to the arytenoid cartilage in back of the larynx. The vocal cords help prevent food entering the lungs and produce sound through vibration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The transitional zone where the cornea becomes continuous with the sclera.

Concepts.definition: The transitional zone where the cornea becomes continuous with the sclera.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A centrally placed component of the ventricular system of the brain located in the diencephalon. Cerebrospinal fluid from the lateral ventricles flows into the third ventricle via the foramina of Monroe and exits the third ventricle via the aqueduct of Sylvius. The thalamus and hypothalamus border the lateral walls of the third ventricle.

Concepts.definition: A centrally placed component of the ventricular system of the brain located in the diencephalon. Cerebrospinal fluid from the lateral ventricles flows into the third ventricle via the foramina of Monroe and exits the third ventricle via the aqueduct of Sylvius. The thalamus and hypothalamus border the lateral walls of the third ventricle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A diamond-shaped cavity filled with cerebrospinal fluid within the pons extending between the obex in the caudal medulla and the aqueduct of Sylvius in the cerebellum.

Concepts.definition: A diamond-shaped cavity filled with cerebrospinal fluid within the pons extending between the obex in the caudal medulla and the aqueduct of Sylvius in the cerebellum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The terminal, cone-shaped end of the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The terminal, cone-shaped end of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The rostral extensions of the ventricular system of the brain consisting of two cavities, one on each side of the brain within the central regions of each cerebral hemisphere.  Cerebrospinal fluid flows from the lateral ventricles into the centrally third ventricle via the foramen of Monroe.

Concepts.definition: The rostral extensions of the ventricular system of the brain consisting of two cavities, one on each side of the brain within the central regions of each cerebral hemisphere.  Cerebrospinal fluid flows from the lateral ventricles into the centrally third ventricle via the foramen of Monroe.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The branch of the brachial artery that passes down the forearm.

Concepts.definition: The branch of the brachial artery that passes down the forearm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A terminal branch of the brachial artery arising just below the elbow that runs along the ulna into the wrist with numerous branches supplying the forearm, wrist and hand.

Concepts.definition: A terminal branch of the brachial artery arising just below the elbow that runs along the ulna into the wrist with numerous branches supplying the forearm, wrist and hand.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A network of nerve fibers that are derived from the anterior rami of spinal nerves L4-L5 and S1-S4, and which are part of the larger lumbosacral plexus, providing motor and sensory innervation for the posterior thigh, most of the lower leg, the entire foot, and part of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: A network of nerve fibers that are derived from the anterior rami of spinal nerves L4-L5 and S1-S4, and which are part of the larger lumbosacral plexus, providing motor and sensory innervation for the posterior thigh, most of the lower leg, the entire foot, and part of the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The area at the center of the kidney. Urine collects here and is funneled into the ureter, the tube that connects the kidney to the bladder.

Concepts.definition: The funnel-shaped proximal portion of the ureter located within the kidney into which urine is secreted, from the collecting duct system of the kidney.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A double-fold of dura mater that lies within the medial longitudinal fissure, and which separates the two cerebral hemispheres. It is attached rostrally to the crista galli and caudally to the surface of the tentorium cerebelli.

Concepts.definition: A double-fold of dura mater that lies within the medial longitudinal fissure, and which separates the two cerebral hemispheres. It is attached rostrally to the crista galli and caudally to the surface of the tentorium cerebelli.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A lymph node which is located above the clavicle.

Concepts.definition: A lymph node which is located above the clavicle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A short duct attached to the gallbladder through which the bile from the gallbladder is secreted in the common bile duct.

Concepts.definition: A short duct attached to the gallbladder through which the bile from the gallbladder is secreted in the common bile duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An embryonic remnant of the mesonephric duct in females that runs parallel to the uterus, cervix and vagina.

Concepts.definition: An embryonic remnant of the mesonephric duct in females that runs parallel to the uterus, cervix and vagina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An accessory pancreatic duct with two branches, one of which opens directly to the duodenum at the minor duodenal papilla while the other connects to the pancreatic duct.

Concepts.definition: An accessory pancreatic duct with two branches, one of which opens directly to the duodenum at the minor duodenal papilla while the other connects to the pancreatic duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Dura mater - the outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the three membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain and spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the three membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain and spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of hinge joint located between the forearm and upper arm.

Concepts.definition: A type of hinge joint located between the forearm and upper arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The layer of connective tissue comprised of the endometrial lining of the uterus which fluctuates in thickness throughout the menstrual cycle.

Concepts.definition: The layer of connective tissue comprised of the endometrial lining of the uterus which fluctuates in thickness throughout the menstrual cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer portion of the nose that protrudes from the face.

Concepts.definition: The outer portion of the nose that protrudes from the face.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the biliary tract outside the liver; the common hepatic duct joins the cystic duct to form the common bile duct.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the biliary tract outside the liver; the common hepatic duct joins the cystic duct to form the common bile duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The arched strip of hair on the bony ridge above each eye socket.

Concepts.definition: The arched strip of hair on the bony ridge above each eye socket.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two folds of a mucous membrane spanning the larynx. The two folds aid in breathing and preventing regurgitation to a greater extent than producing sounds.

Concepts.definition: One of two folds of a mucous membrane spanning the larynx. The two folds aid in breathing and preventing regurgitation to a greater extent than producing sounds.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small triangular process of dura matter beginning at the internal occipital crest just beneath the tentorium and projecting forward.

Concepts.definition: A small triangular process of dura matter beginning at the internal occipital crest just beneath the tentorium and projecting forward.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the digits of the hand.

Concepts.definition: Any of the digits of the hand.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The nail at the end of a finger.

Concepts.definition: The nail at the end of a finger.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure found below the ankle joint.

Concepts.definition: The structure found below the ankle joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

Concepts.definition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone of the skull forming the forehead, root of the nose and the roof of both orbits.

Concepts.definition: A bone of the skull forming the forehead, root of the nose and the roof of both orbits.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large muscle in the back of the lower leg. Its action involves the plantar flexion of the foot.

Concepts.definition: A large muscle in the back of the lower leg. Its action involves the plantar flexion of the foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The anatomical location where the esophagus joins to the stomach.

Concepts.definition: The anatomical location where the esophagus joins to the stomach.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The soft tissue surrounding the neck of individual teeth as well as covering the alveolar bone. The tissue is fibrous and continuous with the periodontal ligament and mucosal covering.

Concepts.definition: The soft tissue surrounding the neck of individual teeth as well as covering the alveolar bone. The tissue is fibrous and continuous with the periodontal ligament and mucosal covering.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

Concepts.definition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A twisted curved structure such as a coil spring or corkscrew.

Concepts.definition: A twisted curved structure such as a coil spring or corkscrew.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the three ducts associated with the liver including the right hepatic duct, left hepatic duct and common hepatic duct.

Concepts.definition: Any of the three ducts associated with the liver including the right hepatic duct, left hepatic duct and common hepatic duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A ball-and-socket joint between the head of the femur and the acetabulum.

Concepts.definition: A ball-and-socket joint between the head of the femur and the acetabulum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Thin membranous tissue that surrounds the vaginal opening.

Concepts.definition: Thin membranous tissue that surrounds the vaginal opening.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A U-shaped bone supporting the tongue. This bone is located at the base of the tongue and is suspended from the tips of the styloid processes of the temporal bones by the stylohyoid ligaments.

Concepts.definition: A U-shaped bone supporting the tongue. This bone is located at the base of the tongue and is suspended from the tips of the styloid processes of the temporal bones by the stylohyoid ligaments.

2. Click on the Mappings tab at the top of the page.
3. In the "Other mappings available for download" section click on the link  ICD-O-3.1 to NCIt Topography Mapping: ICD-O-3.1 to NCIt Topography Mapping (2017-12-21)
4. The file provides the ICD-O Code (col A), ICD-O string (col E), NCIt Code (col G), and NCIt Preferred term (col H).
